      <intermediateExchange id="88b8ed1a-c182-5f81-b866-2edbcac157d4" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="Co" casNumber="000071-48-7" amount="0.0003351154673567065" isCalculatedAmount="true" mathematicalRelation="AcetaldehydeIn*( 1 + 2 ) * (0.05/100) / 3" intermediateExchangeId="521c93e2-96c4-52a2-91d8-ebbdf53ed51a" activityLinkId="8ba385be-554d-5410-a7d4-e7b90ad38728">
        <name xml:lang="en">cobalt acetate</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">As reported in the literature provide below, the acetaldehyde and diluent mixture (with a ratio of 1:2) is introduced in the reactor with the addition of 0.05 to 0.1 % cobalt acetate and copper acetate at 40 °C; the ratio of Co:Cu is 1:2. This, according to the input of acetaldehyde, leads to 0.00165 kg of catalyst input per kg of acetic anhydrite produced.

In Wells (1999) a value of 0.001 kg of catalyst is reported per kg of acetic anhydride produced (for an input of 1.2 kg of acetaldehyde and 2.4 kg of diluent). At the same time, it is also stated that the latter amount can be lower if the catalyst is regenerated and the diluent recycled. 

We, here, use the most conservative value of 0.00165 kg of catalytic system, with a Co:Cu ratio of 1:2.

References:
G. Margaret Wells, “Handbook of Petrochemicals and Processes”, 2nd edition, Ashgate, 1999
Held, H., Rengstl, A., Mayer, D.: Acetic anhydride and mixed fatty acid anhydrides. In: "Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial." 2004

</comment>
